491
00:25:53,306 --> 00:25:57,008
So we're working on a game at Shell Games right now,

492
00:25:57,008 --> 00:25:59,389
all about a virtual chemistry lab.

493
00:25:59,389 --> 00:26:01,450
And originally it was called SuperChem,

494
00:26:01,450 --> 00:26:02,731
and we started trying to figure out,

495
00:26:02,731 --> 00:26:04,152
all right, what are the centers of this?

496
00:26:04,152 --> 00:26:05,532
We knew that our central mechanic

497
00:26:05,532 --> 00:26:07,113
was realistic manipulation.

498
00:26:07,863 --> 00:26:09,644
of laboratory equipment.

499
00:26:09,644 --> 00:26:11,265
We knew that that was central.

500
00:26:11,265 --> 00:26:12,805
If we didn't get that right, we were in trouble.

501
00:26:12,805 --> 00:26:14,646
This is meant to be an educational game,

502
00:26:14,646 --> 00:26:16,026
so it has a transformational goal

503
00:26:16,026 --> 00:26:17,667
of teaching real lab skills.

504
00:26:17,667 --> 00:26:19,987
So if we don't get that right, that's a problem.

505
00:26:19,987 --> 00:26:22,208
So these two things we know are centers.

506
00:26:22,208 --> 00:26:24,489
But then this could be boring, right?

507
00:26:24,489 --> 00:26:26,710
This could end up being like a really boring thing

508
00:26:26,710 --> 00:26:27,550
if we don't do it right.

509
00:26:27,550 --> 00:26:29,531
So we knew a central aspect was

510
00:26:29,531 --> 00:26:31,231
that we needed a strong fantasy.

511
00:26:31,231 --> 00:26:33,352
And we knew that a lot of people have a fantasy

512
00:26:33,352 --> 00:26:36,253
of I'm the lab genius, I'm the mad scientist in the lab.

513
00:26:36,723 --> 00:26:40,484
So we changed it from Superchem to now it's called the HoloLab Champions, right?

514
00:26:40,484 --> 00:26:45,045
And it's all about being the greatest lab worker in the world.

515
00:26:45,045 --> 00:26:49,307
And we found that these three things together by focusing on these as the center,

516
00:26:49,307 --> 00:26:51,527
things are starting to come together with that game.

517
00:26:51,527 --> 00:26:57,029
So another pattern, pattern number three, property number three is boundaries.

518
00:26:58,501 --> 00:27:02,924
Boundaries, as Alexander puts it, they draw attention to the center.

519
00:27:02,924 --> 00:27:04,965
Boundaries create centers.

520
00:27:04,965 --> 00:27:07,947
And right here you see a map of a cathedral here.

521
00:27:07,947 --> 00:27:10,349
And you see how important the boundaries are

522
00:27:10,349 --> 00:27:11,589
in terms of creating centers.

523
00:27:11,589 --> 00:27:14,331
Here's some boundaries in nature.

524
00:27:14,331 --> 00:27:17,994
Here's a cutaway of some wood cells.

525
00:27:17,994 --> 00:27:19,655
Nature is all about the boundaries.

526
00:27:19,655 --> 00:27:21,396
All living things are made out of cells,

527
00:27:21,396 --> 00:27:23,037
and cells have boundaries all over the place.

528
00:27:23,037 --> 00:27:24,838
Check out this door.

529
00:27:24,838 --> 00:27:26,039
It's kind of a cool door.

530
00:27:26,039 --> 00:27:27,340
Looks pretty cool.

531
00:27:27,747 --> 00:27:28,907
I'd be like, I might go in that door.

532
00:27:28,907 --> 00:27:29,388
How about now?

533
00:27:29,388 --> 00:27:29,868
Yeah, right?

534
00:27:29,868 --> 00:27:31,409
Look at all those boundaries.

535
00:27:31,409 --> 00:27:34,551
Boundaries make things important.

536
00:27:34,551 --> 00:27:37,033
Boundary, boundary, boundary, boundary.

537
00:27:37,033 --> 00:27:38,935
You'll find the fancier any picture is,

538
00:27:38,935 --> 00:27:42,317
the more boundaries it has on the frame going around it.

539
00:27:42,317 --> 00:27:44,078
Because there's something about boundaries

540
00:27:44,078 --> 00:27:46,180
that creates strong centers, makes things important.

541
00:27:46,751 --> 00:27:49,133
Now in game design, we know all about boundaries.

542
00:27:49,133 --> 00:27:51,695
So many games are all about boundaries and boundary lines

543
00:27:51,695 --> 00:27:53,316
and cross this line and cross that line

544
00:27:53,316 --> 00:27:55,978
and complete this goal and complete that goal.

545
00:27:55,978 --> 00:27:57,820
We're all about boundaries in game design.

546
00:27:57,820 --> 00:28:00,802
But what about in our narrative design?

547
00:28:00,802 --> 00:28:02,663
Are there boundaries there?

548
00:28:02,663 --> 00:28:04,865
Well, they show up in surprising places

549
00:28:04,865 --> 00:28:06,586
if you talk about the hero's journey.

550
00:28:06,586 --> 00:28:08,788
The obvious place they show up there is with thresholds.

551
00:28:08,788 --> 00:28:12,191
Those moments where you cross and you can't come back.

552
00:28:12,191 --> 00:28:13,171
That's really important.

553
00:28:13,171 --> 00:28:15,013
If you don't have good thresholds in your story design,

554
00:28:15,423 --> 00:28:16,764
then you don't have good story.

555
00:28:16,764 --> 00:28:18,785
You've got to have those clear boundaries.

556
00:28:18,785 --> 00:28:22,288
And the most interesting stories are usually

557
00:28:22,288 --> 00:28:25,210
the ones that pit two systems against each other

558
00:28:25,210 --> 00:28:26,671
with conflicting boundaries.

559
00:28:26,671 --> 00:28:29,673
And you have to make a choice about which boundaries you're

560
00:28:29,673 --> 00:28:31,014
going to respect and which boundaries

561
00:28:31,014 --> 00:28:33,856
are going to violate, because that ends up being exciting.

562
00:28:33,856 --> 00:28:35,737
This was part of the idea in Bioshock

563
00:28:35,737 --> 00:28:37,058
with the Little Sisters.

564
00:28:37,657 --> 00:28:41,219
Right? You've got one system that says you want to get as many points as possible.

565
00:28:41,219 --> 00:28:45,482
Well, guess what? In order to get as many points as possible, you're going to need to murder a bunch of little girls.

566
00:28:45,482 --> 00:28:49,885
Or, you can rescue the little girls, but you only get half as many points.

567
00:28:49,885 --> 00:28:57,130
So now your normal sense of decency and its boundaries are put up against the boundaries of winning at the game.

568
00:28:57,130 --> 00:29:01,973
Similarly, Papers, Please is a game that establishes all these rules.

569
00:29:01,973 --> 00:29:04,234
Here's your job. This is what you do.

570
00:29:04,234 --> 00:29:06,396
You need to obey the rules in a certain way.

571
00:29:06,820 --> 00:29:10,282
And then it puts you in situations where, again,

572
00:29:10,282 --> 00:29:13,925
your sense of human decency is like maybe violating the rules

573
00:29:13,925 --> 00:29:15,826
is the right thing in this case.

574
00:29:15,826 --> 00:29:18,428
So the system of rules and the system of what's right

575
00:29:18,428 --> 00:29:19,369
come into conflict.

576
00:29:19,369 --> 00:29:22,291
So I often find that creating the best, most interesting

577
00:29:22,291 --> 00:29:27,215
stories is about boundaries in conflict with each other.

578
00:29:27,215 --> 00:29:30,097
So now a surprising pattern, alternating repetition.

579
00:29:30,097 --> 00:29:34,040
And you can see it illustrated here in the classical egg dark

580
00:29:34,040 --> 00:29:35,441
pattern, which you can see in buildings.

581
00:29:35,750 --> 00:29:37,551
all over the place, outside.

582
00:29:37,551 --> 00:29:40,853
This is a pattern that's been around thousands of years,

583
00:29:40,853 --> 00:29:43,154
will not go away, because we like

584
00:29:43,154 --> 00:29:45,015
alternating repetitions so much.

585
00:29:45,015 --> 00:29:47,156
But wait, isn't repetition boring?

586
00:29:47,156 --> 00:29:49,057
Well, repetition can be boring.

587
00:29:49,057 --> 00:29:51,219
When it's just straight repetition,

588
00:29:51,219 --> 00:29:53,680
it's boring and bad, it has a bad feeling.

589
00:29:53,680 --> 00:29:56,742
But when it's alternating repetition, we love it.

590
00:29:56,742 --> 00:29:59,063
So consider the checkerboard.

591
00:29:59,063 --> 00:30:01,164
We don't have to make checkerboards like this.

592
00:30:01,164 --> 00:30:03,186
We could have made it a piece of graph paper.

593
00:30:03,186 --> 00:30:04,727
But we don't like a piece of graph paper.

594
00:30:05,494 --> 00:30:07,235
we like alternating repetition.

595
00:30:07,235 --> 00:30:09,376
We could have made it a rainbow of squares,

596
00:30:09,376 --> 00:30:11,296
a bunch of different colors, all different colors.

597
00:30:11,296 --> 00:30:12,297
No, no, no, no, no.

598
00:30:12,297 --> 00:30:15,818
Alternating repetition is what we like as humans.

599
00:30:15,818 --> 00:30:18,119
And we see this everywhere.

600
00:30:18,119 --> 00:30:18,999
Everybody knows, you know,

601
00:30:18,999 --> 00:30:21,420
anyone here is gonna know about the flow channel,

602
00:30:21,420 --> 00:30:24,061
keeping your game kind of on that wonderful place

603
00:30:24,061 --> 00:30:25,782
between boredom and anxiety,

604
00:30:25,782 --> 00:30:27,302
in that wonderful state of flow,

605
00:30:27,302 --> 00:30:29,463
and you increase your flow over time.

606
00:30:29,463 --> 00:30:30,544
But of course, we all know

607
00:30:30,544 --> 00:30:32,504
that's not really the right way to do it.

608
00:30:32,504 --> 00:30:34,905
That's the right way to do it, right?

609
00:30:35,214 --> 00:30:38,076
You get a little bored because it's a little too easy.

610
00:30:38,076 --> 00:30:39,517
And oh my god, it got so hard.

611
00:30:39,517 --> 00:30:41,318
And now, I get a little bit of a break.

612
00:30:41,318 --> 00:30:43,100
You get a tension and then a release.

613
00:30:43,100 --> 00:30:45,541
A tension and then a release.

614
00:30:45,541 --> 00:30:47,443
That's a pattern that we like.

615
00:30:47,443 --> 00:30:49,684
And of course, you see this in games like Flame in the Flood.

616
00:30:49,684 --> 00:30:52,306
You have these horrible, intense experiences on the islands.

617
00:30:52,306 --> 00:30:54,067
And now, I'm back on the river.

618
00:30:54,067 --> 00:30:55,168
And it's OK.

619
00:30:55,168 --> 00:30:55,849
And I can relax.

620
00:30:55,849 --> 00:30:57,229
And all right, I'm getting ready.

621
00:30:57,229 --> 00:30:57,970
I'm relaxed enough.

622
00:30:57,970 --> 00:30:59,391
It's actually getting a little boring here on the river.

623
00:30:59,391 --> 00:31:00,472
I'm going to go back on the island.

624
00:31:00,472 --> 00:31:01,953
And it's going to get exciting again.

625
00:31:02,700 --> 00:31:05,202
And even in one of the most classic patterns of game

626
00:31:05,202 --> 00:31:07,763
narrative, the string of pearls or the rivers and lakes

627
00:31:07,763 --> 00:31:09,524
approach, where you have a cut scene and a level,

628
00:31:09,524 --> 00:31:10,425
and a cut scene and a level.

629
00:31:10,425 --> 00:31:14,447
And as much as people sometimes deride that pattern,

630
00:31:14,447 --> 00:31:16,308
the reason the pattern doesn't go away

631
00:31:16,308 --> 00:31:19,110
is because it's wonderful alternating repetition.

632
00:31:19,110 --> 00:31:21,431
We like to kind of take a break and sort of see

633
00:31:21,431 --> 00:31:23,833
what's going on, and get set up for the next thing,

634
00:31:23,833 --> 00:31:26,214
and then get all active, and then take a break.

635
00:31:26,214 --> 00:31:29,476
So it's alternating repetition that feels really good.

636
00:31:31,472 --> 00:31:36,216
The fifth pattern took me a while to understand, the pattern he calls positive space.

637
00:31:36,216 --> 00:31:40,699
And what's weird about it is what he's saying is that things that are well designed don't

638
00:31:40,699 --> 00:31:46,523
just have a good shape unto themselves, like here's this ancient bowl that has kind of

639
00:31:46,523 --> 00:31:52,887
a cool shape, but also the negative space around them also has a good shape.

640
00:31:52,887 --> 00:31:58,931
So if you look at the shape around the bowl, it actually is kind of a cool, pleasing shape.

641
00:31:58,931 --> 00:31:59,852
As a counterexample...

642
00:32:00,333 --> 00:32:01,993
Here's a sculpture that's just kind of, you know,

643
00:32:01,993 --> 00:32:03,954
modern sculpture right there.

644
00:32:03,954 --> 00:32:06,374
And it's kind of a cool shape by itself.

645
00:32:06,374 --> 00:32:09,855
But the space around it doesn't really have much of a shape.

646
00:32:09,855 --> 00:32:12,275
And as a result, the thing is just kind of a little bit

647
00:32:12,275 --> 00:32:12,515
blah.

648
00:32:12,515 --> 00:32:16,296
So we see this spatially in games all the time, right?

649
00:32:16,296 --> 00:32:18,797
There's a Monument Valley level right there.

650
00:32:18,797 --> 00:32:20,977
And you see it's got a cool shape all by itself.

651
00:32:20,977 --> 00:32:23,538
But also look at the negative space around it.

652
00:32:23,538 --> 00:32:26,378
Those are good, interesting shapes.

653
00:32:27,120 --> 00:32:30,182
But what does this mean in the world of narrative?

654
00:32:30,182 --> 00:32:33,704
What does positive and negative space mean in narrative?

655
00:32:33,704 --> 00:32:38,847
And I think, I sometimes think the right way

656
00:32:38,847 --> 00:32:42,750
to think about it is positive space can be dialogue,

657
00:32:42,750 --> 00:32:44,111
is a kind of positive space.

658
00:32:44,111 --> 00:32:46,332
So what is that negative space then?

659
00:32:46,332 --> 00:32:49,574
Well, it's either silence or someone else's dialogue.

660
00:32:49,574 --> 00:32:53,937
And this is illustrated incredibly well in Oxenfree.

661
00:32:53,937 --> 00:32:56,179
If people have played this, this is

662
00:32:56,179 --> 00:32:56,719
so masterfully.

663
00:32:57,253 --> 00:33:01,797
created. Because like a lot of games, you make these little choices. Here are your different

664
00:33:01,797 --> 00:33:06,762
text choices. Lots of games have this. But what's so artfully done in Oxenfree is you

665
00:33:06,762 --> 00:33:11,807
don't have to pick one of the choices. Silence is an option. And then something else will

666
00:33:11,807 --> 00:33:12,228
happen.

667
00:33:12,807 --> 00:33:14,808
And so if you want to, you can be silent.

668
00:33:14,808 --> 00:33:17,429
And then more than just silence being an option, when

669
00:33:17,429 --> 00:33:18,650
you pick these is up to you.

670
00:33:18,650 --> 00:33:21,471
It's not like someone talks and then they wait, like

671
00:33:21,471 --> 00:33:22,431
normal games.

672
00:33:22,431 --> 00:33:25,453
In Oxenfree, the dialogue options come up while someone

673
00:33:25,453 --> 00:33:27,874
else is talking, and you can interrupt them at any time.

674
00:33:27,874 --> 00:33:30,455
And sometimes interrupting them is fine and the right

675
00:33:30,455 --> 00:33:31,196
thing to do.

676
00:33:31,196 --> 00:33:32,777
Sometimes it's incredibly insulting.

677
00:33:32,777 --> 00:33:36,518
And other times, saying anything at all is a bad idea

678
00:33:36,518 --> 00:33:38,920
because someone is saying something very important.

679
00:33:38,920 --> 00:33:40,260
And you want to say something.

680
00:33:40,655 --> 00:33:46,297
but actually restraining yourself and letting the other person talk is the better choice.

681
00:33:46,297 --> 00:33:50,799
So it's more natural, it's more like things are in the real world, and again, it has this

682
00:33:50,799 --> 00:33:53,840
idea of positive and negative space in dialogue.

683
00:33:53,840 --> 00:33:58,182
Another pattern is the idea of good shape.

684
00:33:58,182 --> 00:34:04,505
He makes a simple observation that things that are well-constructed and meet their own

685
00:34:04,505 --> 00:34:10,267
purposes and do so well and help everyone out, they tend to take on shapes.

686
00:34:10,735 --> 00:34:12,896
that are just beautiful by themselves.

687
00:34:12,896 --> 00:34:17,377
And so in some ways, good shape is kind of a signifier

688
00:34:17,377 --> 00:34:20,598
that yeah, you probably did this right.

689
00:34:20,598 --> 00:34:24,198
Like look at this boat sail, right?

690
00:34:24,198 --> 00:34:27,659
Man, that just looks so strong and so powerful.

691
00:34:27,659 --> 00:34:30,260
And of course it wasn't designed to be beautiful,

692
00:34:30,260 --> 00:34:34,661
it was designed to maximize its ability to move the boat.

693
00:34:34,661 --> 00:34:37,741
Now we have good shapes in games all the time, right?

694
00:34:37,741 --> 00:34:38,642
There's a little.

695
00:34:38,873 --> 00:34:41,736
It's a little bit of Legend of Zelda shape right there.

696
00:34:41,736 --> 00:34:44,058
Here's one I like, a classic, Phoenix.

697
00:34:44,058 --> 00:34:46,981
That's kind of a cool shape on that big boss monster.

698
00:34:46,981 --> 00:34:48,983
This, I believe, is the first boss monster

699
00:34:48,983 --> 00:34:51,706
in the history of gaming, is that guy in Phoenix.

700
00:34:51,706 --> 00:34:55,029
But sort of what's so cool about this as a shape,

701
00:34:55,029 --> 00:34:57,832
it's not just designed to be pretty, it's functional.

702
00:34:58,228 --> 00:35:02,129
The whole idea is you're going to shoot holes in all that orange mass underneath

703
00:35:02,129 --> 00:35:04,389
because you've got to shoot that purple guy in the middle.

704
00:35:04,389 --> 00:35:07,370
And of course, he's really hard to shoot because you've got to clear this big tunnel

705
00:35:07,370 --> 00:35:09,711
because there's so much stuff around him.

706
00:35:09,711 --> 00:35:13,992
But the secret strategy is that purple ribbon under him is a rotating ribbon

707
00:35:13,992 --> 00:35:15,472
and you need to shoot holes in that.

708
00:35:15,472 --> 00:35:18,313
But what you can do is move over to the side,

709
00:35:18,313 --> 00:35:20,454
shoot along the side and get holes in the ribbon

710
00:35:20,454 --> 00:35:23,114
and get the ribbon all busted up and then go back to the middle

711
00:35:23,114 --> 00:35:24,375
because the middle is dangerous

712
00:35:24,375 --> 00:35:26,555
because that dude is dropping all these things on you.

713
00:35:27,198 --> 00:35:29,800
So, because everything's functional in the game,

714
00:35:29,800 --> 00:35:32,622
like, there's just this good shape naturally emerges from it.

715
00:35:32,622 --> 00:35:35,183
And shapes can be spatial, but when, again,

716
00:35:35,183 --> 00:35:38,186
when you get into the world of narrative,

717
00:35:38,186 --> 00:35:40,547
like, what is, what are shapes,

718
00:35:40,547 --> 00:35:43,109
what do we mean by good shape?

719
00:35:43,109 --> 00:35:46,671
I think sometimes we need to think of good shape

720
00:35:46,671 --> 00:35:48,112
in terms of time.

721
00:35:48,112 --> 00:35:52,155
Having the right shape of interaction over time is important.

722
00:35:52,852 --> 00:35:57,115
One of the things I was blown away when I first played

723
00:35:57,115 --> 00:36:00,838
the interactive Walking Dead by a few different things.

724
00:36:00,838 --> 00:36:04,761
So traditionally when we've had interactive dialogue moments

725
00:36:04,761 --> 00:36:06,182
we put them at important times.

726
00:36:06,182 --> 00:36:09,665
Now of course that means you're respecting

727
00:36:09,665 --> 00:36:11,826
the story first of all.

728
00:36:11,826 --> 00:36:12,947
Walking Dead didn't do that.

729
00:36:12,947 --> 00:36:15,889
Walking Dead said no the most important thing is

730
00:36:15,889 --> 00:36:19,032
rhythm of interaction is most important.

731
00:36:19,032 --> 00:36:21,393
There's a shape of interaction that we like.

732
00:36:21,790 --> 00:36:25,751
And we're going to give you dialogue interactions at that rhythm, so it feels good, so it feels

733
00:36:25,751 --> 00:36:26,051
natural.

734
00:36:26,051 --> 00:36:31,033
But you're like, ah, but what if some of those, what if those dialogue things don't mean anything?

735
00:36:31,033 --> 00:36:31,813
That's okay.

736
00:36:31,813 --> 00:36:34,754
A lot of things we say don't mean anything.

737
00:36:34,754 --> 00:36:35,695
And that's okay.

738
00:36:35,695 --> 00:36:38,376
Now, the problem is that creates a bad ambiguity.

739
00:36:38,376 --> 00:36:41,837
How do I know if something I said was helpful or not helpful?

740
00:36:41,837 --> 00:36:46,259
And these guys had the insight to when you do something that really makes a difference,

741
00:36:46,259 --> 00:36:49,660
this little thing pops up, that so and so will remember that.

742
00:36:49,660 --> 00:36:49,840
Right?

743
00:36:51,456 --> 00:36:55,480
And personally, I feel like that was a really good shape that

744
00:36:55,480 --> 00:36:58,002
kind of came out of thoughtful design.

745
00:36:58,002 --> 00:37:01,745
So here's a surprising pattern, local symmetries.

746
00:37:01,745 --> 00:37:04,908
This is not an obvious idea at first.

747
00:37:04,908 --> 00:37:08,431
We all are always told that symmetrical things are

748
00:37:08,431 --> 00:37:11,553
beautiful and beauty is symmetry, et cetera, et cetera.

749
00:37:11,553 --> 00:37:13,135
But look at this building.

750
00:37:13,135 --> 00:37:15,017
That's not a very symmetrical building.

751
00:37:15,017 --> 00:37:18,580
But then you notice, this is the Alhambra here.

752
00:37:19,002 --> 00:37:25,967
It is full of small symmetries, little symmetrical rectangular spaces, symmetrical rotational

753
00:37:25,967 --> 00:37:26,888
spaces.

754
00:37:26,888 --> 00:37:30,351
It's a bunch of local symmetries all glued together.

755
00:37:30,351 --> 00:37:35,975
And this was, I'd never heard anyone make this observation before, that many great,

756
00:37:35,975 --> 00:37:40,018
wonderful, persistent things are local symmetries all glued together.

757
00:37:40,018 --> 00:37:43,000
The human body is certainly this way.

758
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:46,723
Our hands are a local symmetry with each other, but they're not symmetrical with our feet.

759
00:37:47,215 --> 00:37:49,537
And it wouldn't be better if they were, right?

760
00:37:49,537 --> 00:37:52,339
That wouldn't necessarily be a good thing.

761
00:37:52,339 --> 00:37:54,680
And certainly, look at our organs inside the body.

762
00:37:54,680 --> 00:37:56,881
Some of them are symmetrical with each other.

763
00:37:56,881 --> 00:37:57,542
Others are not.

764
00:37:57,542 --> 00:38:00,844
And then they're all kind of glued together, these very

765
00:38:00,844 --> 00:38:03,786
different things, with each one having its own symmetry,

766
00:38:03,786 --> 00:38:05,887
all kind of stuck together.

767
00:38:05,887 --> 00:38:07,608
Where do we see this in games?

768
00:38:07,608 --> 00:38:10,210
Well, here's a map of the original Zelda.

769
00:38:11,060 --> 00:38:11,700
I mean, look at that.

770
00:38:11,700 --> 00:38:13,201
It's like the map of the Alhambra.

771
00:38:13,201 --> 00:38:16,082
There's no overall symmetry, because overall symmetry

772
00:38:16,082 --> 00:38:17,182
isn't helpful.

773
00:38:17,182 --> 00:38:20,444
But look at all the local symmetries.

774
00:38:20,444 --> 00:38:23,565
Look at all the little local symmetries all glued together.

775
00:38:23,565 --> 00:38:26,807
Now, when it comes to stories, I am less clear

776
00:38:26,807 --> 00:38:28,808
at what relevance this has.

777
00:38:28,808 --> 00:38:31,449
I'm a little stumped by this, honestly.

778
00:38:31,449 --> 00:38:35,831
I have an instinct that it has something to do with characters.

779
00:38:35,831 --> 00:38:37,412
When I see a bunch of characters that

780
00:38:37,412 --> 00:38:38,492
are all different from each other,

781
00:38:39,223 --> 00:38:40,823
and they're all kind of brought together.

782
00:38:40,823 --> 00:38:43,404
Like this feels like local symmetries to me,

783
00:38:43,404 --> 00:38:45,284
but I feel like there's something deeper

784
00:38:45,284 --> 00:38:47,144
with local symmetries in narrative

785
00:38:47,144 --> 00:38:48,765
that I don't understand yet.

786
00:38:48,765 --> 00:38:51,105
But let's press on.

787
00:38:51,105 --> 00:38:53,286
Pattern eight, deep interlock.

788
00:38:53,286 --> 00:38:55,666
And actually, as the way Alexander puts it,

789
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:57,727
ambiguity and deep interlock.

790
00:38:57,727 --> 00:38:59,747
And normally we think of ambiguity as bad,

791
00:38:59,747 --> 00:39:03,068
but what he's talking about is an ambiguity

792
00:39:03,068 --> 00:39:05,168
where you have two things interacting with each other

793
00:39:05,168 --> 00:39:06,788
in such a powerful way.

794
00:39:07,287 --> 00:39:10,849
that it's hard to give attribution to either one of them.

795
00:39:10,849 --> 00:39:12,650
So here's some Inca stone carving

796
00:39:12,650 --> 00:39:15,392
where these stones just fit together perfectly

797
00:39:15,392 --> 00:39:16,453
and beautifully.

798
00:39:16,453 --> 00:39:19,735
And which one defines the space over the other?

799
00:39:19,735 --> 00:39:23,057
I mean, this is the idea of the dovetail joint, right?

800
00:39:23,057 --> 00:39:24,397
Neither one is in charge.

801
00:39:24,397 --> 00:39:26,679
It's only because they are both perfectly,

802
00:39:26,679 --> 00:39:30,461
deeply interlocked that you have something

803
00:39:30,461 --> 00:39:32,162
that's strong and solid.

804
00:39:32,916 --> 00:39:34,157
We see this in games.

805
00:39:34,157 --> 00:39:37,959
Certainly, the game of Go is all about deep interlock.

806
00:39:37,959 --> 00:39:39,920
There's nothing to push against in the game

807
00:39:39,920 --> 00:39:41,181
except the other player.

808
00:39:41,181 --> 00:39:42,722
And everything that one player does

809
00:39:42,722 --> 00:39:45,703
is defined by pushing against the other player.

810
00:39:45,703 --> 00:39:49,386
And each game ends up being its own kind of organism and entity

811
00:39:49,386 --> 00:39:53,768
the way things are pushed together.

812
00:39:53,768 --> 00:39:59,091
Terence Lee talks about the idea of two kinds of stories

813
00:39:59,091 --> 00:39:59,692
in every game.

814
00:40:00,241 --> 00:40:04,804
that there is the explicit story, which is the one the designer is trying to tell.

815
00:40:04,804 --> 00:40:07,525
But then there is the player's story.

816
00:40:07,525 --> 00:40:12,768
The story of what the player is experiencing, the story that's happening to them.

817
00:40:12,768 --> 00:40:18,072
And when those line up, it feels great, and when those don't line up, it's super bad.

818
00:40:18,478 --> 00:40:23,622
Like maybe you've got a situation where you as the designer, you gave a sidekick to the character,

819
00:40:23,622 --> 00:40:26,764
and you're like, yeah, I've got this awesome sidekick, and I think it's great, and I think it's funny,

820
00:40:26,764 --> 00:40:30,066
and the player's like, I hate this guy. I totally hate this sidekick.

821
00:40:30,066 --> 00:40:34,669
And then you create a situation where, oh no, the sidekick fell in a well!

822
00:40:34,669 --> 00:40:36,490
You've got to help out the sidekick!

823
00:40:36,490 --> 00:40:39,652
And the player might be like, no, screw that, right?

824
00:40:39,652 --> 00:40:44,996
I'm so glad that guy fell in a well. Do I really have to rescue that guy? I really don't want to.

825
00:40:44,996 --> 00:40:47,397
That's terrible. That means everything's falling apart.

826
00:40:47,757 --> 00:40:52,698
in your story because you don't have good deep interlock between the player's story

827
00:40:52,698 --> 00:40:53,858
and the explicit story.

828
00:40:53,858 --> 00:40:59,540
And this is one of the first games I experienced that did this really well was Planetfall,

829
00:40:59,540 --> 00:41:02,360
you know, the old Steve Moretzky game here.

830
00:41:02,360 --> 00:41:08,602
He creates this beautiful sidekick, this character named Floyd, who's funny and cute and you

831
00:41:08,602 --> 00:41:12,463
just can't help but be super entertained by Floyd.

832
00:41:12,463 --> 00:41:14,903
And so as a result, when

833
00:41:15,277 --> 00:41:20,979
horrible things happen to Floyd, you're like, no, you're like, it's a big deal.

834
00:41:20,979 --> 00:41:28,121
And I've talked to many people where this was the first time they cried during a game

835
00:41:28,121 --> 00:41:30,702
was in Planetfall because these things were just so well aligned.

836
00:41:30,702 --> 00:41:33,724
Yes, so there's your deep interlock, see, between, yeah, okay, you got it.

837
00:41:33,724 --> 00:41:38,705
All right, next pattern is contrast.

838
00:41:38,705 --> 00:41:43,327
Okay, I love this, this bowl, and Alexander has a picture of the bowl in his book and he...

839
00:41:43,600 --> 00:41:47,924
He points out how the two opposites really make this one unity.

840
00:41:47,924 --> 00:41:50,305
They really bring things together.

841
00:41:50,305 --> 00:41:53,268
And contrast, of course, does make things stronger,

842
00:41:53,268 --> 00:41:56,550
but often in surprising ways.

843
00:41:56,550 --> 00:42:00,033
Zippy the Pinhead, via Bill Griffith,

844
00:42:00,033 --> 00:42:03,436
once had a long expostulation about the nature of comedy,

845
00:42:03,436 --> 00:42:08,880
where he points out that all comedy is the unity of opposites.

846
00:42:08,880 --> 00:42:11,001
I'll let you think about that for a minute.

847
00:42:11,001 --> 00:42:11,822
Right there.

848
00:42:12,466 --> 00:42:17,409
the unity of opposites. But it's true. All comedy is the unity of opposites. Like this

849
00:42:17,409 --> 00:42:27,034
sign. Right? It's funny because these two things should not be together. Or I saw this

850
00:42:27,034 --> 00:42:39,381
sign in Newcastle. Right? And that's how comedy works. And comedy is really important in our

851
00:42:39,381 --> 00:42:40,382
stories, right?

852
00:42:40,860 --> 00:42:45,203
understanding how to get that contrast, how to get the two opposites together and bring

853
00:42:45,203 --> 00:42:47,865
them together in a surprising way is important.

854
00:42:47,865 --> 00:42:55,390
And this brings me to Undertale, which of course has a lot of really wonderful, funny

855
00:42:55,390 --> 00:43:01,614
moments in it, but at the same time, it has a lot of really serious moments in it.

856
00:43:01,614 --> 00:43:06,017
So it's a weird game because it's very silly and very serious.

857
00:43:06,017 --> 00:43:08,559
But now I ask you the question.

858
00:43:09,560 --> 00:43:14,822
Would Undertale be more serious if you took the funny parts out?

859
00:43:14,822 --> 00:43:18,223
And would it be funnier if you took the serious parts out?

860
00:43:18,223 --> 00:43:20,463
The answer in both cases, I think, is no.

861
00:43:20,463 --> 00:43:24,064
The serious parts make the funny parts funny,

862
00:43:24,064 --> 00:43:28,545
and the funny parts make the serious parts more serious.

863
00:43:28,545 --> 00:43:30,486
That is the magic of contrast.

864
00:43:30,486 --> 00:43:34,467
It requires a certain bravery to use it,

865
00:43:34,467 --> 00:43:37,528
but when you do, it can be used to really, really great effect.

866
00:43:39,116 --> 00:43:42,897
So the next one is gradients or graded variation.

867
00:43:42,897 --> 00:43:46,259
And this is just an observation that when things change

868
00:43:46,259 --> 00:43:48,780
gradually, that is sometimes beautiful.

869
00:43:48,780 --> 00:43:50,820
We talked about boundaries when things change suddenly.

870
00:43:50,820 --> 00:43:56,923
But also a gradual change can be a beautiful thing.

871
00:43:56,923 --> 00:43:59,564
And I had to rack my brain a bit to think about gradual

872
00:43:59,564 --> 00:44:02,705
changes in games, because we often have very punctuated

873
00:44:02,705 --> 00:44:03,285
changes.

874
00:44:03,662 --> 00:44:07,064
in games. Gradual changes are often more hidden and subtle.

875
00:44:07,064 --> 00:44:12,708
But one that I thought of, a recent game, Jason Rohrer's new game, One Hour,

876
00:44:12,708 --> 00:44:18,673
One Life. I don't know if people are familiar with this game, but

877
00:44:18,673 --> 00:44:21,134
the idea is that you log into this world

878
00:44:21,134 --> 00:44:23,556
and you are a baby. You come into the world as a baby.

879
00:44:23,556 --> 00:44:27,999
And you're going to live one hour. But in that one hour, you're going to go from

880
00:44:27,999 --> 00:44:32,603
a baby to a very old person. And at the end of that hour, you're going to die.

881
00:44:33,802 --> 00:44:36,103
But it's a persistent world.

882
00:44:36,103 --> 00:44:39,365
And so the changes that you make will be permanent.

883
00:44:39,365 --> 00:44:42,827
And when you log in in the future as a new person,

884
00:44:42,827 --> 00:44:45,548
generations down the road, you will

885
00:44:45,548 --> 00:44:47,549
have a mother and father in the game,

886
00:44:47,549 --> 00:44:49,911
and the world will be persistent.

887
00:44:49,911 --> 00:44:52,132
And part of the power of the game

888
00:44:52,132 --> 00:44:56,054
is that gradual change over the course of an hour.

889
00:44:56,054 --> 00:44:59,817
So finding those gradual changes can be important.

890
00:45:01,398 --> 00:45:05,522
Pattern 11 is very counterintuitive, the idea of roughness.

891
00:45:05,522 --> 00:45:08,785
Now normally we think of roughness as a bad thing.

892
00:45:08,785 --> 00:45:10,827
We want to smooth things out, we want to sand things,

893
00:45:10,827 --> 00:45:15,331
we want to polish things, we want to take away all roughness.

894
00:45:15,331 --> 00:45:19,034
But what he points out is that roughness often

895
00:45:19,034 --> 00:45:23,478
is part of what makes things great and real.

896
00:45:23,478 --> 00:45:26,460
I love his picture of this house, which in a lot of ways

897
00:45:26,460 --> 00:45:28,602
seems kind of like an atrocity, right?

898
00:45:29,049 --> 00:45:32,310
The lines don't line up right, it's very inconsistent,

899
00:45:32,310 --> 00:45:37,311
but there's a very human, peaceful quality about it.

900
00:45:37,311 --> 00:45:42,592
One example I think about a lot is pure vanilla extract.

901
00:45:42,592 --> 00:45:45,172
If you go to the grocery store, you have a choice.

902
00:45:45,172 --> 00:45:47,013
You can buy pure vanilla extract,

903
00:45:47,013 --> 00:45:52,574
or for a dollar less, imitation vanilla flavor.

904
00:45:52,574 --> 00:45:55,154
Now what's the difference between these things?

905
00:45:55,154 --> 00:45:57,175
You think, oh well, one comes from real vanilla.

906
00:45:57,467 --> 00:46:00,467
The other, I don't know, comes from some lab, whatever.

907
00:46:00,467 --> 00:46:02,768
It's something that smells like vanilla,

908
00:46:02,768 --> 00:46:04,188
but is in no way vanilla.

909
00:46:04,188 --> 00:46:07,209
And that is completely wrong.

910
00:46:07,209 --> 00:46:10,710
In truth, both of them contain the same thing.

911
00:46:10,710 --> 00:46:13,651
A bunch of vanillin molecule, C8H8O3,

912
00:46:13,651 --> 00:46:16,872
suspended in an alcohol solution.

913
00:46:16,872 --> 00:46:19,513
That's what both of these are.

914
00:46:19,513 --> 00:46:21,873
The only difference is where it comes from.

915
00:46:21,873 --> 00:46:24,734
The pure vanilla extract comes from the vanilla plant.

916
00:46:24,734 --> 00:46:26,675
The imitation vanilla flavor.

917
00:46:27,197 --> 00:46:31,380
comes from a process of pouring acid on paper pulp that just happens to create this same

918
00:46:31,380 --> 00:46:32,240
molecule.

919
00:46:32,240 --> 00:46:35,202
But you're getting exactly the same thing.

920
00:46:35,202 --> 00:46:41,025
Well, not exactly the same thing, because the imitation stuff is actually pure.

921
00:46:41,025 --> 00:46:47,649
It's nothing but alcohol and vanilla molecule, whereas the pure vanilla extract is not pure.

922
00:46:47,649 --> 00:46:53,913
It has all this extra junk that is not vanilla that comes from the vanilla plant but is not

923
00:46:53,913 --> 00:46:55,333
the thing that smells like vanilla.

924
00:46:56,104 --> 00:46:59,385
But the reason we favor that one is because of all that junk.

925
00:46:59,385 --> 00:47:01,806
We like all that weird rough junk.

926
00:47:01,806 --> 00:47:06,307
It makes everything feel broader and more interesting and more complex.

927
00:47:06,307 --> 00:47:11,368
So this is a case where purity actually gets you in trouble.

928
00:47:11,368 --> 00:47:12,389
Purity isn't as good.

929
00:47:12,389 --> 00:47:14,169
Roughness ends up being better.

930
00:47:15,025 --> 00:47:19,367
Who, for example, would pay to go and see the perfectly straight Tower of Pisa?

931
00:47:19,367 --> 00:47:21,368
Nobody would do that, right?

932
00:47:21,368 --> 00:47:23,910
It's the roughness that makes it interesting.

933
00:47:23,910 --> 00:47:30,212
I once heard Peter Molyneux talk about the idea that the greatest difficulty for game

934
00:47:30,212 --> 00:47:31,253
artists is dirt.

935
00:47:31,253 --> 00:47:35,055
That getting things to look dirty is so hard.

936
00:47:35,055 --> 00:47:39,737
And it's true, and it's important to make things look dirty because they give things

937
00:47:39,737 --> 00:47:40,637
a roughness.

938
00:47:40,637 --> 00:47:42,778
In sports, any ball.

939
00:47:43,190 --> 00:47:44,890
that you have in a sporting game.

940
00:47:44,890 --> 00:47:46,971
They're not perfectly smooth.

941
00:47:46,971 --> 00:47:49,032
If they're ever touched by human hands,

942
00:47:49,032 --> 00:47:50,813
they're not perfectly smooth.

943
00:47:50,813 --> 00:47:52,834
It's the roughness that defines them.

944
00:47:52,834 --> 00:47:55,875
The roughness is how we interact with them.

945
00:47:55,875 --> 00:47:57,736
Think of a game like Monopoly.

946
00:47:57,736 --> 00:47:59,277
What is Monopoly?

947
00:47:59,277 --> 00:48:00,497
It's a landlord simulator.

948
00:48:00,497 --> 00:48:03,498
You're gonna be a landlord and do landlord things.

949
00:48:03,498 --> 00:48:04,559
Okay, awesome.

950
00:48:04,559 --> 00:48:06,320
What are the avatars gonna be?

951
00:48:06,320 --> 00:48:08,841
All right, they're gonna be this.

952
00:48:08,841 --> 00:48:09,441
What?

953
00:48:09,983 --> 00:48:14,844
Shouldn't they be that little Monopoly dude with the mustache and six different colors?

954
00:48:14,844 --> 00:48:15,045
Nope!

955
00:48:15,045 --> 00:48:20,646
There's going to be a hat and a battleship and a shoe and a d- what are you doing?

956
00:48:20,646 --> 00:48:24,666
What kind of screwed up game design is this?

957
00:48:24,666 --> 00:48:26,287
Right?

958
00:48:26,287 --> 00:48:32,448
And I often think of what Goethe said, all lyrical work must, as a whole, be perfectly

959
00:48:32,448 --> 00:48:37,229
intelligible, but in some particulars a little unintelligible.

960
00:48:38,015 --> 00:48:43,738
I'm sure he was thinking about Monopoly when he wrote that.

961
00:48:43,738 --> 00:48:51,663
If Minecraft was all beautiful, polished environments, would it be better?

962
00:48:51,663 --> 00:48:53,844
No. No. The roughness is important.

963
00:48:53,844 --> 00:48:55,164
Okay, pattern 12, echoes.

964
00:48:55,164 --> 00:48:59,827
Echoes is an interesting idea. I love this little hut.

965
00:48:59,827 --> 00:49:01,388
I think it's in Turkey here, this little house.

966
00:49:01,388 --> 00:49:04,670
And you see these sort of echoes of design.

967
00:49:04,670 --> 00:49:06,050
Look at how the roof caps...

968
00:49:06,433 --> 00:49:08,815
echo each other even though they're a little different from each other.

969
00:49:08,815 --> 00:49:14,419
And then even the doorway has a very similar shape and angle to the roof peaks.

970
00:49:14,419 --> 00:49:16,580
And it kind of connects everything together.

971
00:49:16,580 --> 00:49:21,084
So Alexander often talks about making sure the angles of different things are connected

972
00:49:21,084 --> 00:49:22,965
and that helps bring an overall connectedness.

973
00:49:22,965 --> 00:49:27,808
His counter example is this interesting building actually created by Michelangelo.

974
00:49:28,499 --> 00:49:31,260
But when you look at this building, it's not really great.

975
00:49:31,260 --> 00:49:34,340
Like nothing connects to anything else very well.

976
00:49:34,340 --> 00:49:35,500
The angles are all different.

977
00:49:35,500 --> 00:49:37,021
The shapes are all different.

978
00:49:37,021 --> 00:49:38,961
It's a little bit of a hodgepodge.

979
00:49:38,961 --> 00:49:42,682
There's a big overall symmetry for no good reason.

980
00:49:42,682 --> 00:49:44,562
And then there's these local symmetries,

981
00:49:44,562 --> 00:49:47,203
but nothing connects and it just doesn't feel so great.

982
00:49:47,203 --> 00:49:50,123
So in games we do this all the time.

983
00:49:50,123 --> 00:49:52,464
We did this in our Water Bears VR game.

984
00:49:52,464 --> 00:49:54,684
We'd had this initial tablet-based game

985
00:49:54,684 --> 00:49:56,145
called Water Bears, which was all about.

986
00:49:56,498 --> 00:49:58,719
bringing colored water to these cute little water bears.

987
00:49:58,719 --> 00:50:00,119
And we made a VR version.

988
00:50:00,119 --> 00:50:02,400
And we said, wow, this is so relaxing to play this.

989
00:50:02,400 --> 00:50:04,781
Since it's a relaxing game, let's

990
00:50:04,781 --> 00:50:06,222
put it in a relaxing setting.

991
00:50:06,222 --> 00:50:08,903
So we put it in this kind of Caribbean setting.

992
00:50:08,903 --> 00:50:10,583
It's very relaxing.

993
00:50:10,583 --> 00:50:13,524
It kind of echoes the nature of the gameplay.

994
00:50:13,524 --> 00:50:15,985
A less relaxing game, Night in the Woods,

995
00:50:15,985 --> 00:50:20,047
is also full of echoes.

996
00:50:20,047 --> 00:50:23,828
This is a game that is all about growing up,

997
00:50:23,828 --> 00:50:24,488
moving from.

998
00:50:24,802 --> 00:50:29,945
the world of childhood to the world of adulthood and how you have to give things up in order

999
00:50:29,945 --> 00:50:30,685
to do that.

1000
00:50:30,685 --> 00:50:37,950
And so in doing so, they made the characters all very cartoony, childlike characters, but

1001
00:50:37,950 --> 00:50:44,694
they put them in very adult situations, thus kind of echoing the whole theme and sort of

1002
00:50:44,694 --> 00:50:46,295
playing up that contrast.

1003
00:50:46,295 --> 00:50:50,338
Another great example of echoes I like is Cuphead.

1004
00:50:51,436 --> 00:50:55,621
Cuphead, even though it's, you know, maybe not the deepest game narrative in the world,

1005
00:50:55,621 --> 00:51:02,188
it has a really nice connection between what you do in the game and the overall story.

1006
00:51:02,188 --> 00:51:03,809
So really, what's Cuphead about?

1007
00:51:03,809 --> 00:51:07,073
This is a game about jumping into danger, right?

1008
00:51:07,073 --> 00:51:10,776
So our story is that these two cup-headed brothers...

1009
00:51:11,170 --> 00:51:13,051
They were gambling with the devil.

1010
00:51:13,051 --> 00:51:14,952
They knew it was dangerous, right?

1011
00:51:14,952 --> 00:51:17,353
But they jumped right in and they gambled with the devil.

1012
00:51:17,353 --> 00:51:20,015
They lost, so they lost their souls.

1013
00:51:20,015 --> 00:51:20,875
So what's the solution?

1014
00:51:20,875 --> 00:51:23,337
The devil says, well, I've got a bunch of people

1015
00:51:23,337 --> 00:51:25,198
I need you to collect contracts from.

1016
00:51:25,198 --> 00:51:26,398
It's gonna be super dangerous.

1017
00:51:26,398 --> 00:51:28,780
And they're like, all right, let's go do it.

1018
00:51:28,780 --> 00:51:30,881
And so they go and jump into danger.

1019
00:51:30,881 --> 00:51:32,922
Here's an example of some danger jumping here.

1020
00:51:32,922 --> 00:51:36,684
Right, so this game is so freaking hard.

1021
00:51:36,684 --> 00:51:37,725
You see that little pink thing?

1022
00:51:37,725 --> 00:51:39,045
That's actually kind of important.

1023
00:51:41,177 --> 00:51:41,878
Boink.

1024
00:51:41,878 --> 00:51:43,161
Jumping on those pink things.

1025
00:51:43,161 --> 00:51:47,832
So those pink things are what's in the game.

1026
00:51:47,832 --> 00:51:48,995
It's called a parry move.

1027
00:51:49,482 --> 00:51:51,284
Those pink things will kill you.

1028
00:51:51,284 --> 00:51:54,086
If you just jump on them, you'll just die.

1029
00:51:54,086 --> 00:51:57,129
But if you time it just right, right here,

1030
00:51:57,129 --> 00:51:58,730
you can take a look, here's some more of them.

1031
00:51:58,730 --> 00:52:01,252
If you time it just right and you hit the jump button

1032
00:52:01,252 --> 00:52:03,354
a second time while you're in the air,

1033
00:52:03,354 --> 00:52:05,496
your character spins a little bit, turns pink,

1034
00:52:05,496 --> 00:52:07,537
and then will hit the pink thing

1035
00:52:07,537 --> 00:52:11,461
and build up all these bonus attacks that you can use later.

1036
00:52:11,461 --> 00:52:13,002
If this was me doing this scene,

1037
00:52:13,002 --> 00:52:14,763
I would have died six times by now.

1038
00:52:15,159 --> 00:52:20,101
because I would have hit the parry button at the wrong time and hit the ghost and I'd be dead.

1039
00:52:20,101 --> 00:52:23,763
So you've got a story all about characters who jump into danger

1040
00:52:23,763 --> 00:52:29,806
and then you have a central mechanic that is about literally jumping into danger.

1041
00:52:29,806 --> 00:52:34,048
And you could argue that these guys took this nature of echoes a little too far

1042
00:52:34,048 --> 00:52:38,530
because, you know, there they are, the Moldenhauer brothers.

1043
00:52:38,882 --> 00:52:43,904
You know, two brothers who initiated this game here,

1044
00:52:43,904 --> 00:52:47,685
and there's Maya, their cousin, kind of talking about it.

1045
00:52:47,685 --> 00:52:48,966
They jumped in on a thing.

1046
00:52:48,966 --> 00:52:51,767
They did not know what they were doing.

1047
00:52:51,767 --> 00:52:52,047
Right?

1048
00:52:52,047 --> 00:52:55,208
I mean, here's the initial frame from the Cuphead trailer.

1049
00:52:55,208 --> 00:52:56,569
You'll notice, coming 2015.

1050
00:52:57,252 --> 00:52:59,653
You had a game, I mean, and this is the second one,

1051
00:52:59,653 --> 00:53:00,954
the original trailer said coming 2014, right?

1052
00:53:00,954 --> 00:53:02,354
So this game was three years late,

1053
00:53:02,354 --> 00:53:05,575
and they never would have been able to do it

1054
00:53:05,575 --> 00:53:10,097
if they hadn't done a deal with Microsoft, right?

1055
00:53:10,097 --> 00:53:12,258
In order to do it, and I don't wanna say

1056
00:53:12,258 --> 00:53:13,979
Microsoft's like the devil, but like,

1057
00:53:13,979 --> 00:53:19,201
it's possible to take the Echo thing a little too far

1058
00:53:19,201 --> 00:53:21,361
is all I'm saying right there.

1059
00:53:21,361 --> 00:53:21,741
All right.

1060
00:53:25,585 --> 00:53:30,547
three more patterns here. One of them is the void. And this is a little bit of a strange pattern,

1061
00:53:30,547 --> 00:53:36,990
a void where nothing is there. This picture is a picture actually from my house when my wife and I

1062
00:53:36,990 --> 00:53:40,992
moved into the house we live in about 15 years ago. We picked it up at, I don't know, Target or

1063
00:53:40,992 --> 00:53:46,274
Marshalls or something. We're like, oh, this looks kind of cool. And my fascination with this picture

1064
00:53:46,274 --> 00:53:51,696
is just never ending. Even though, what is it? It's just some leaves. But what gets me is that

1065
00:53:51,696 --> 00:53:52,476
black square.

1066
00:53:53,595 --> 00:53:57,037
Right? Close one eye and put a finger up and cover the black square.

1067
00:53:57,037 --> 00:54:00,219
And you'll see this is a completely unremarkable picture.

1068
00:54:00,219 --> 00:54:05,143
And then you take that finger away and you're like,

1069
00:54:05,143 --> 00:54:09,666
black square, what are you doing there?

1070
00:54:09,666 --> 00:54:10,887
Why are you there?

1071
00:54:10,887 --> 00:54:13,228
And this void pattern shows up in lots of places.

1072
00:54:13,228 --> 00:54:15,130
Every church has the void pattern inside it,

1073
00:54:15,130 --> 00:54:18,072
because that's where important things happen.

1074
00:54:18,072 --> 00:54:20,353
The human heart, what does it have?

1075
00:54:20,353 --> 00:54:22,094
A lot of complex structure in there?

1076
00:54:22,094 --> 00:54:22,595
No, empty.

1077
00:54:22,954 --> 00:54:25,396
it's empty inside there, right?

1078
00:54:25,396 --> 00:54:28,819
The most important things are empty inside.

1079
00:54:28,819 --> 00:54:32,482
And part of the reason that's important

1080
00:54:32,482 --> 00:54:35,966
is because when you enter an empty space,

1081
00:54:35,966 --> 00:54:39,529
suddenly you become very important

1082
00:54:39,529 --> 00:54:43,032
and everything you do becomes very important.

1083
00:54:43,032 --> 00:54:44,513
We see this in the hero's journey.

1084
00:54:44,513 --> 00:54:46,735
There's always that moment of entering the cave, right?

1085
00:54:46,735 --> 00:54:48,196
The cave is this kind of empty space

1086
00:54:48,196 --> 00:54:51,339
where something very important is going to happen.

1087
00:54:51,528 --> 00:54:53,609
We see it in video games all the time.

1088
00:54:53,609 --> 00:54:56,070
Like, a boss monster battle never happens

1089
00:54:56,070 --> 00:54:57,711
in a linen closet.

1090
00:54:57,711 --> 00:55:00,033
It always happens when you come into a big, empty space

1091
00:55:00,033 --> 00:55:04,475
and you're like, oh, I think things are going to happen

1092
00:55:04,475 --> 00:55:05,836
right now.

1093
00:55:05,836 --> 00:55:10,018
I see a bunch of local symmetries in an empty space

1094
00:55:10,018 --> 00:55:12,379
and I think, oh yeah, oh yeah,

1095
00:55:12,379 --> 00:55:13,980
something's going to happen right now.

1096
00:55:13,980 --> 00:55:17,282
So the void is very important.

1097
00:55:17,282 --> 00:55:19,803
And of course, think about void in terms of storytelling.

1098
00:55:21,443 --> 00:55:28,984
If we talk about positive and negative space being dialogue and silence, the use of silence

1099
00:55:28,984 --> 00:55:31,425
is often very, very powerful that way.

1100
00:55:31,425 --> 00:55:38,406
And many games, I think Undertale is a great example, have found clever ways to sort of

1101
00:55:38,406 --> 00:55:41,407
use silence in order to deliver power.

1102
00:55:41,407 --> 00:55:45,368
The 14th pattern is simplicity and inner calm.

1103
00:55:45,368 --> 00:55:50,449
The idea being that when...

1104
00:55:50,708 --> 00:55:56,294
everything unessential is stripped away and you only have what's needed,

1105
00:55:56,294 --> 00:56:00,158
there is a certain calm quality because nothing else is needed.

1106
00:56:00,158 --> 00:56:04,282
Everything is here, as simple as it can be, and there's a perfect

1107
00:56:04,282 --> 00:56:08,106
quality about it. These pillars holding up a shrine,

1108
00:56:08,106 --> 00:56:11,149
a Japanese shrine, are one of Alexander's

1109
00:56:11,149 --> 00:56:13,332
examples, and he points out that

1110
00:56:14,214 --> 00:56:17,036
These things are not trying to be what they are.

1111
00:56:17,036 --> 00:56:20,878
They're just usually serving an unusual purpose

1112
00:56:20,878 --> 00:56:22,939
in the simplest way possible.

1113
00:56:22,939 --> 00:56:24,720
And that often gives them this sort of strength

1114
00:56:24,720 --> 00:56:25,400
and inner calm.

1115
00:56:25,400 --> 00:56:28,081
Now simplicity and complexity we talk about

1116
00:56:28,081 --> 00:56:30,123
all the time in games.

1117
00:56:30,123 --> 00:56:31,303
And it's tricky, right?

1118
00:56:31,303 --> 00:56:32,504
Because you hear people say,

1119
00:56:32,504 --> 00:56:34,105
oh I hate that game, it's too complex.

1120
00:56:34,105 --> 00:56:35,285
And you hear people say,

1121
00:56:35,285 --> 00:56:36,606
I hate that game, it's too simple.

1122
00:56:36,606 --> 00:56:37,666
Well, what does that mean?

1123
00:56:37,666 --> 00:56:40,388
Somewhere in the middle is right?

1124
00:56:40,388 --> 00:56:42,169
No, we know simple games are better,

1125
00:56:42,169 --> 00:56:43,530
except when it's the bad kind of simple.

1126
00:56:43,931 --> 00:56:45,953
What? What does that mean?

1127
00:56:45,953 --> 00:56:48,695
Well, part of the idea is there are two kinds of complexity.

1128
00:56:48,695 --> 00:56:50,856
One of them is innate complexity.

1129
00:56:50,856 --> 00:56:53,418
Believe it or not, what you're looking at right there

1130
00:56:53,418 --> 00:56:56,360
is a single board game experience.

1131
00:56:56,360 --> 00:56:57,481
Someone took all these board games

1132
00:56:57,481 --> 00:56:59,943
and made one set of rules for how you play all of them

1133
00:56:59,943 --> 00:57:02,265
in a big connected sequence.

1134
00:57:02,265 --> 00:57:03,946
There is a lot of innate complexity.

1135
00:57:03,946 --> 00:57:07,709
Learning the rules takes quite some time there.

1136
00:57:07,709 --> 00:57:09,230
As opposed to a game like Go,

1137
00:57:09,230 --> 00:57:12,452
which is a very complex game, but not.

1138
00:57:13,323 --> 00:57:19,508
innately. The complexity is emergent because of the clever way that the centers and the

1139
00:57:19,508 --> 00:57:24,591
patterns push up against each other. One of the best ways to build towards that kind of

1140
00:57:24,591 --> 00:57:30,156
simplicity is to give things multiple purposes. Again, going back to Pac-Man, because I just

1141
00:57:30,156 --> 00:57:36,641
love Pac-Man so much, the dots in Pac-Man, they seem so simple. They're just dots. Who

1142
00:57:36,641 --> 00:57:40,443
cares? But when you count up their purposes, there's many of them.

1143
00:57:41,174 --> 00:57:44,397
First, your goal. Eat all the dots on the level.

1144
00:57:44,397 --> 00:57:46,698
So now they've established my goal for the game.

1145
00:57:46,698 --> 00:57:51,302
They give me points, and points are my judgment of how good I am at the game.

1146
00:57:51,302 --> 00:57:53,423
They create a pleasing sound of progress.

1147
00:57:53,423 --> 00:57:57,146
Waka waka waka. Every time I eat a dot, no waka waka when I don't eat dots.

1148
00:57:57,146 --> 00:57:59,908
So you get this kind of nice feedback loop of progress.

1149
00:57:59,908 --> 00:58:03,110
This is how I get extra lives. I've got to eat dots to get points.

1150
00:58:03,110 --> 00:58:04,271
Points get me extra lives.

1151
00:58:04,271 --> 00:58:07,974
So in order to survive in the game, the dots make me survive.

1152
00:58:08,975 --> 00:58:10,375
And where's the progress meter?

1153
00:58:10,375 --> 00:58:11,656
I don't need a progress meter.

1154
00:58:11,656 --> 00:58:15,297
The dots simply, at a glance, show me my progress.

1155
00:58:15,297 --> 00:58:15,657
I don't need it.

1156
00:58:15,657 --> 00:58:16,837
They've solved that purpose.

1157
00:58:16,837 --> 00:58:19,038
And then they have a secret purpose

1158
00:58:19,038 --> 00:58:20,438
very few people know about.

1159
00:58:20,438 --> 00:58:23,159
Every time you eat a dot in Pac-Man,

1160
00:58:23,159 --> 00:58:24,960
it slows you down just a little bit.

1161
00:58:24,960 --> 00:58:27,541
It kicks you back just a little bit.

1162
00:58:27,541 --> 00:58:31,022
And that's enough to make you go just a little slower

1163
00:58:31,022 --> 00:58:33,243
down a dot hallway than an empty hallway.

1164
00:58:33,243 --> 00:58:34,083
And guess what?

1165
00:58:34,083 --> 00:58:36,023
What speeds do the ghosts go?

1166
00:58:36,826 --> 00:58:41,208
The ghosts go a little slower than you in an empty hallway

1167
00:58:41,208 --> 00:58:44,209
and a little faster than you in a dot hallway.

1168
00:58:44,209 --> 00:58:47,630
So suddenly you have this very interesting strategic decision

1169
00:58:47,630 --> 00:58:48,310
to make.

1170
00:58:48,310 --> 00:58:52,932
The final pattern is not separateness.

1171
00:58:52,932 --> 00:58:54,472
What does that mean?

1172
00:58:54,472 --> 00:58:57,874
Well, he's talking about things being connected to each other

1173
00:58:57,874 --> 00:58:59,034
in a fundamental way.

1174
00:58:59,034 --> 00:59:00,455
I love this picture.

1175
00:59:00,455 --> 00:59:03,656
This picture he has of a path made of these stones connected

1176
00:59:03,656 --> 00:59:04,016
together.

1177
00:59:04,463 --> 00:59:06,764
And of course, so many of the patterns are seen here.

1178
00:59:06,764 --> 00:59:09,085
You see the stones are connected to the earth,

1179
00:59:09,085 --> 00:59:11,666
but all the stones are actually the same.

1180
00:59:11,666 --> 00:59:13,347
They're not different stones.

1181
00:59:13,347 --> 00:59:14,548
They're just turned at an angle.

1182
00:59:14,548 --> 00:59:15,988
They're all the same square.

1183
00:59:15,988 --> 00:59:18,310
So you have this perfect echo along them.

1184
00:59:18,310 --> 00:59:20,030
And then you have alternating repetition,

1185
00:59:20,030 --> 00:59:20,991
and then you have a gradient,

1186
00:59:20,991 --> 00:59:22,071
and you have everything here.

1187
00:59:22,071 --> 00:59:23,632
Everything is connected.

1188
00:59:23,632 --> 00:59:26,193
And one of my favorite games in this regard

1189
00:59:26,193 --> 00:59:28,575
is Brothers, A Tale of Two Sons.

1190
00:59:28,575 --> 00:59:31,576
This is just a gorgeous, beautiful game,

1191
00:59:31,576 --> 00:59:32,437
and it's so clever.

1192
00:59:32,853 --> 00:59:35,635
The idea of it is these two brothers going on an adventure,

1193
00:59:35,635 --> 00:59:38,037
and you're going to control both of them.

1194
00:59:38,037 --> 00:59:41,720
And you do one with each one of your hands.

1195
00:59:41,720 --> 00:59:43,641
One hand controls one brother, one hand

1196
00:59:43,641 --> 00:59:45,663
controls the other brother.

1197
00:59:45,663 --> 00:59:48,605
And you solve a lot of interesting puzzles and things

1198
00:59:48,605 --> 00:59:50,766
by moving these two brothers together.

1199
00:59:50,766 --> 00:59:53,829
Now, of course, this works with the human neurology,

1200
00:59:53,829 --> 00:59:57,491
because one hand is controlled by one half the brain,

1201
00:59:57,491 --> 01:00:00,874
the other hand is controlled by the other half of the brain.

1202
01:00:02,074 --> 01:00:05,996
And the only way they communicate is up the middle, up the corpus colossum there.

1203
01:00:05,996 --> 01:00:11,980
And so it's almost like the two halves of the brain, which sort of behave like siblings,

1204
01:00:11,980 --> 01:00:14,141
now actually get to be siblings in the game.

1205
01:00:14,141 --> 01:00:18,484
And then, now I'm going to give a spoiler, cover your ears and sing if you really don't

1206
01:00:18,484 --> 01:00:21,606
want to know, something bad happens to one of the brothers.

1207
01:00:21,606 --> 01:00:29,330
And you'll never feel so alone in your life when suddenly that brother is gone because

1208
01:00:29,330 --> 01:00:30,031
half of your brain.

1209
01:00:30,680 --> 01:00:33,642
is now unable to participate in the game.

1210
01:00:33,642 --> 01:00:36,143
And then cleverly what happens next in the game

1211
01:00:36,143 --> 01:00:39,404
is so beautiful that I think it will make anyone cry.

1212
01:00:39,404 --> 01:00:44,207
And so it's a great example of deep interlock

1213
01:00:44,207 --> 01:00:46,147
between the player's story and the game's story,

1214
01:00:46,147 --> 01:00:47,548
but it takes it farther.

1215
01:00:47,548 --> 01:00:51,150
It's not just the explicit story and the game's story,

1216
01:00:51,150 --> 01:00:53,251
but it goes actually into the psychology

1217
01:00:53,251 --> 01:00:55,312
and even the neurology of the player.

1218
01:00:55,312 --> 01:00:56,912
And there's this beautiful connectedness

1219
01:00:56,912 --> 01:00:58,013
and non-separateness.

1220
01:00:58,475 --> 01:01:00,715
that happens between all three of these things.

1221
01:01:00,715 --> 01:01:04,456
And for me, this is why games that aren't just fun,

1222
01:01:04,456 --> 01:01:06,596
but games that actually change us as people,

1223
01:01:06,596 --> 01:01:08,417
games that educate, games that transform,

1224
01:01:08,417 --> 01:01:10,437
are so important.

1225
01:01:10,437 --> 01:01:11,997
Because great games, they change us,

1226
01:01:11,997 --> 01:01:16,758
and they make us better at connecting with each other,

1227
01:01:16,758 --> 01:01:20,919
and they make us better at connecting with the entire world,

1228
01:01:20,919 --> 01:01:23,780
